Black Limba is known for its grey and dark color, with occasional black streaks or patterns, and a distinctive grain that can range from straight to interlocked, creating a visually dynamic surface.

In terms of physical properties, Black Limba is a relatively lightweight hardwood with a medium to coarse texture. It has a moderate to high stiffness and good bending strength, making it a suitable material for carving. Black Limba is also a durable wood, with good resistance to decay and insect damage. Overall, its unique combination of aesthetic and physical properties makes it a sought-after material for high-end woodworking projects.

Hard maple:

One of the key benefits of hard maple for carving is its extreme hardness. This makes it a very strong and durable wood that can withstand heavy use and wear.

Hard maple is also known for its ability to take on a beautiful finish. Its fine, uniform texture makes it easy to sand to a smooth and glossy surface. It has tight and even grain.=
Overall, hard maple is a versatile and highly desirable hardwood for carving, offering extreme hardness, workability, resistance to staining and warping, and the ability to take on a beautiful finish.

Wood Color: Red oak typically has a light to medium reddish-brown color. This can add warmth and a rustic touch to your sculpture.
Grain Pattern: Red oak is known for its prominent and open grain pattern with a coarse texture. This can give your sculpture a more textured and pronounced appearance.
Durability: Red oak is moderately durable. While it can withstand wear and tear, it may not be the best choice for outdoor sculptures exposed to the elements.
Janka Hardness: Red oak has a Janka hardness rating of approximately 1,290 lbf, which means it's relatively hard and can resist denting.
White Oak Sculpture:

Wood Color: White oak exhibits a light to medium brown color with a grayish or olive tint. It imparts a more neutral and classic look to your sculpture.
Grain Pattern: White oak offers a fine and even grain with a closed, non-prominent grain pattern. This results in a smoother, more uniform appearance for your sculpture.
Durability: White oak is highly durable and is exceptionally resistant to decay and rot. It's a top choice for sculptures exposed to outdoor conditions.
Janka Hardness: White oak has a Janka hardness rating of approximately 1,360 lbf, making it even harder than red oak and more resistant to damage.
When choosing between red oak and white oak for your sculpture, consider the aesthetics you prefer and where the sculpture will be displayed. Red oak may be suitable for indoor use, especially if you appreciate a textured, warm appearance. White oak, on the other hand, is an excellent choice for outdoor sculptures or if you desire a smoother, classic look that can withstand the elements.

Ultimately, your choice should align with your artistic vision and the environment in which the sculpture will be showcased. Both types of oak offer unique qualities that can enhance the beauty of your artwork.
